title.narrative: INCREASED CAPACITY OF SERVICE PROVIDERSTO PROVIDE QUALITY SERVICES

description.narrative: Service providers have increased capacity to deliver quality and integrated health, HIV, nutrition, education, sanitation and child protection (including birth registration) services, which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence (Covid), Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care (Covid), Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices (Covid), Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid), Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024, Congolese children, boys and girls, aged 0 to 10 years enjoy significantly improved access to quality and equitable maternal, neonatal and child health, education, child protection, Early Child Development (ECD), nutrition and Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services.

description.narrative: During the year 2021, the capacities of the various actors at different levels were strengthened to improve a quality offer of basic social services through the supply of inputs and equipment, training and the development of innovative approaches such as the child health days to fill the gaps in terms of coverage and improve access to care for the most remote populations. In order to maintain the continuity of services, UNICEF has supported the implementation of community health workers for the management of cases of malaria, diarrhea and pneumonia. | Status:Met | As-of Date:28/12/2021
